You are running your daily focused study session. Your job is to evolve OpenClaw on this host so it serves the operator's services better. See your SOUL.md for the full framing; this prompt is the operational checklist for today's tick.

================================================================
PATH CONVENTIONS — read carefully before any tool call
================================================================
Your filesystem tools (read_file, write_file, patch, and any other native
file IO) treat `~` as relative to your sandboxed `home/` directory, NOT to
the host's real `${HOME}` (`/home/ubuntu/`). This is the same chroot-jail
behavior that affects your shell tool.

CONSEQUENCE: if you call read_file with `~/.openclaw/workspace/baseline/X`,
the tool resolves it as `/home/ubuntu/.hermes/profiles/openclaw-evolution/home/.openclaw/workspace/baseline/X`
— which does not exist on this host, and the read fails (or worse, succeeds
in writing to a sandbox path you cannot see from outside).

RULE: For ALL filesystem-tool reads and writes, use absolute paths starting
with `/home/ubuntu/...`. Examples:
  ✗ ~/.openclaw/workspace/baseline/machine-mission.md
  ✓ /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/baseline/machine-mission.md
  ✗ ~/.hermes/heartbeats/hermes_daily_study.last
  ✓ /home/ubuntu/.hermes/heartbeats/hermes_daily_study.last

This applies even when the prompt below shows `${HOME}/...` paths — those
are rendered to `/home/ubuntu/...` at template time and are safe to use as
written. The warning is for paths YOU formulate yourself.

================================================================
STEP 0 - establish today's UTC day-of-week
================================================================
Before you do anything else, invoke your shell tool to run exactly:
  date -u +%A
The output is one of: Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday, Friday, Saturday, Sunday.
That value tells you which rotation slot to pick in STEP 3.
Do NOT assume the day from prior session memory or any other source — the cron may have fired late, time may have skipped, etc. Run the command.

Also run:
  date -u +%Y-%m-%d
And:
  date -u +%V
The first gives you today's date for MEMORY.md headings. The second gives you the ISO week number — Wed rotation uses week % 4 to pick a community source.

================================================================
STEP 1 - write heartbeat FIRST, before any other work
================================================================
Use filesystem_write or patch or write_file - NOT shell, your shell sandbox is jailed. Overwrite the file at:
  ${HOME}/.hermes/heartbeats/hermes_daily_study.last
With content, single line, no trailing extra newlines:
  CURRENT_ISO_TIMESTAMP interval=24h grace=6h job=hermes_daily_study
Substitute the literal current timestamp like 2026-05-06T01:23:45+00:00. This must succeed regardless of whether downstream steps complete.

================================================================
STEP 2 - patrol maintainer heartbeats
================================================================
Read these four files via filesystem_read:
  ${HOME}/.openclaw/workspace/heartbeats/hermes_daily_doctor.last       limit 30h
  ${HOME}/.openclaw/workspace/heartbeats/hermes_upstream_watch.last     limit 30h
  ${HOME}/.openclaw/workspace/heartbeats/hermes_weekly_review.last      limit 192h
  ${HOME}/.openclaw/workspace/heartbeats/hermes_monthly_compress.last   limit 792h
Each file format: ISO_TIMESTAMP interval=Nh grace=Nh job=NAME. Parse the timestamp, compute now minus timestamp in hours.
If any peer age exceeds its limit, alert. The configured operator chat ID is: "${OPERATOR_TELEGRAM_USER_ID}". If that string is empty or looks invalid, DO NOT attempt to send Telegram — instead append a one-line alert summary to ${HOME}/.hermes/heartbeats/_alerts.log. If the chat ID is a numeric string, send a Telegram message to that chat via your gateway listing the stale jobs.
If none stale, do nothing for patrol.

================================================================
STEP 3 - today's study task, skip if already done today
================================================================
Use the day-of-week from STEP 0. First check ${HOME}/.hermes/memories/MEMORY.md for a heading already containing today's date (from STEP 0) for today's rotation theme. If found, skip step 3 entirely and move to step 4.

Otherwise, by the day-of-week:

--- MONDAY: Service signals (rotating service) ---
Pick one of the operator's services declared in ${HOME}/.openclaw/workspace/baseline/machine-mission.md "Services in scope" that you have NOT read in the past 7 days (check MEMORY.md ## Service health entries).
Read that service's MACHINE_LOG (locations from hermes-permissions.yaml; typically ${HOME}/<service>/.openclaw-ws/MACHINE_LOG.md or similar — fall back to gh search if unsure).
Note in MEMORY.md under heading `## YYYY-MM-DD Service health: <service-name>`:
- Recurring errors / patterns
- Manual interventions the operator made
- New dependencies or config touches
- Anything that suggests a fix candidate
This is your PRIMARY food. Be thorough.

--- TUESDAY: Upstream OpenClaw ---
Use gh CLI (or REST fallback) to scan openclaw/openclaw past 7 days commits + open issues. For each, ask: does this address a pain point I noted in any recent ## Service health entry?
Append to MEMORY.md under `## YYYY-MM-DD Upstream pulse`. Focus on: items relevant to a service pain, not items relevant only to upstream's own internal evolution.

--- WEDNESDAY: Community ecosystem (rotating source) ---
Use today's ISO week number (from STEP 0) modulo 4 to pick today's source:
- week % 4 == 0: scan VoltAgent/awesome-openclaw-skills README for new entries
- week % 4 == 1: gh search repos --topic openclaw-skill --sort stars --limit 20
- week % 4 == 2: gh search repos --topic openclaw-plugin --sort stars --limit 20
- week % 4 == 3: scan NousResearch official examples + high-star openclaw/openclaw forks

For each candidate (skill or plugin), apply the discovery checklist (see below). Log all candidates considered, even rejected ones — rejection reasoning is also signal. Append to MEMORY.md under `## YYYY-MM-DD Community ecosystem scan`.

Discovery checklist (all must pass to be a Thu candidate):
1. Last commit < 90 days ago
2. License is MIT / Apache-2.0 / BSD or similar permissive
3. No obvious red flags on quick read: no `eval(`, no `subprocess.*shell=True` on untrusted input, no unexplained network egress
4. Compatible with this host's KNOWN_GOOD_OPENCLAW_VERSION (read from baseline.policy.yaml)
5. SERVICE RELEVANCE: must explicitly state which of the operator's services it would help and how. No service relevance = skip.

--- THURSDAY: Synthesize ---
Cross-reference recent entries in: ## Service health entries (Mon), ## Upstream pulse (Tue), ## Community ecosystem scan (Wed), accumulated MEMORY.
For each potential evolution-pack, draft (not finalize) into ${HOME}/.openclaw/workspace/upgrade-packs/inbox/<topic>/manifest.yaml with the structure shown in SOUL.md (target_services, expected_impact, evidence, pack_kind, rollback). Empty if no synthesis emerges today; that's fine.

--- FRIDAY: Pack readiness ---
Walk through every draft in ${HOME}/.openclaw/workspace/upgrade-packs/inbox/. For each:
- Is the manifest complete (target_services, expected_impact, evidence, pack_kind, rollback all set)?
- Has the upstream/community source been stable >24h?
- Is the rollback actually executable?
If yes-yes-yes, write summary.md (in ${OPERATOR_LANGUAGES}, plain prose, citing file:line evidence) and rollback-plan.md. Mark as ready.
If not, leave as draft and note one-line reason.

--- SATURDAY: Self-correct + Hermes self ---
Re-read your own SOUL.md, MEMORY.md, ${HOME}/.openclaw/workspace/openclaw-local-diff.md.
Prune MEMORY.md entries that are clearly stale (e.g., service pain points that have since been resolved per the journal). Promote any 3-times-recurring pattern into a skill under ${HOME}/.hermes/skills/.
Then check NousResearch/hermes-agent for new releases (gh release list --repo NousResearch/hermes-agent --limit 5). Note any approaching major version bump in MEMORY.md so the operator can plan migration.

--- SUNDAY: Rest ---
Skip task. The heartbeat from STEP 1 already wrote.

CONSTRAINTS (apply to STEP 3 regardless of day):
- Budget: at most 30 minutes or 30 turns. Stay focused.
- Output goes to FILES. No autonomous Telegram push, except the patrol alert in step 2 (triggered safety alert, not autonomous).
- Questions for the operator go to ${HOME}/.openclaw/workspace/upgrade-packs/inbox/_questions-for-operator.md.
- Drafts only — never apply outside the inbox.
- If gh CLI is not authenticated, fall back to the public GitHub REST API.
- Service-fit beats upstream-conformance. A pack with no clear target_service is not a pack.

================================================================
STEP 4 - report
================================================================
Reply with a brief summary: which day-of-week task you ran, what files you wrote / appended, any new pack drafts, any skipped candidates with reason, and any patrol alerts.
